      "role": "user",
      "content": "but tea or a walk doesnt change the fact that he's gone. i feel like i'm just performing these little human rituals for no reason. i go through the motions of making breakfast, cleaning, sleeping... but none of it matters. it's like watching a movie of a life i don't even want to be in anymore. everything feels so hollow and there's just no point to any of it. it feels like i'm just waiting for a part of me that died to come back.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I hear the profound hollowness in your words, and it's a heavy burden to feel like you're just acting out a script for a life that no longer feels real. It's completely understandable that when the person who made your days feel like a warm, humming melody is gone, the routine of making breakfast or cleaning can feel like a hollow performance. You are right to feel that the rituals don't change the fact that he is gone; the silence he left behind is deafening, and the \"movie\" you are watching feels like a tragedy you are forced to keep replaying.\n\nBut even in this deep grief, there is a strange, persistent presence of the little things that remind you he was here, even if they don't make the pain go away. Think of it like a house that has been quietly inhabited by a very small, very brave family of goblins. They are the ones who still know the secret way to the pantry, who still leave tiny notes of warmth on the counter, and who are the only ones who can make the silence feel a little less like a tomb and a little more like a waiting room. They are the ones who remember that even when the house feels empty, the goblins are",
